animal.description:
Meet Buddy, a 14-yr old senior Staffordshire Terrier boy who found himself at the shelter as an owner surrender. All this sweetie asks for is a soft bed in a household where he can live out his life. He does well with other dogs, big and small as long as they are calm like he is. Buddy is considered blind, and sees with his heart, but his Foster says he gets around just great and will follow her into the yard to do his potty. A house with no stairs to the yard is required. He can navigate small steps just fine. Buddy is gentle, housebroken and could stand to lose a few pounds. He’s waiting to meet you ??  Buddy is currently in a foster home.  

Notes from Buddy's foster...
1) Sleeps through the night in X-pen with camera where I can check on him. I play soft music for him when in X-pen. 

2) Wakes around daylight - take him out immediately. Will pee, sometimes poop. (He has had zero accidents in the house to date so 100% housetrained.)

3) Back inside for breakfast- 1 level cup kibble with some wet I/d food on top 

4) Outside again to finish his pee pee as he only goes a little bit on his first out. Second time out he urinates a lot!

5) Back inside for vitamins, joint supplements and back to resting in his soft orthopedic bed.

6) Several pee pee breaks during day - no special times he’ll get anxious if it’s time to go out.

7) Dinner around 4:30pm is 3/4 cup kibble with I/d wet on top. Out to potty.

8) Bedtime is 8pm here. One last potty break, lights out, soft music on all night in his room. Yes, he CAN hear.

Buddy sleeps all night once he settles (11 hours usually)

He is able to walk through my house easily but I keep him on slip lead because I have slick wood laminate floors. His adopter may want to use some carpet runners in areas where he has to get up and down as it makes it easier on him. 

He steps down two small 6-8” steps to get into my secure courtyard to exercise & potty. I make sure he walks around for daily exercise as he needs to lose weight (he follows me off leash).

He has zero reaction to my two 18-lb female ShihTzu or my 6-lb female Pomeranian and they have no reaction to him, but I’m still cautious and keep him on slip lead when passing them.


How to adopt: You must be an approved adopter to VIEW our animals. If you find an animal that you are interested in, please complete an online adoption application. All adoptable animals are first come, first serve, and the application does not guarantee the availability of a specific animal or adoption approval.

animal.description:
Josie is the sweetest, 4-5 year old, 45 lb mix..mix of what is anyones guess- probably some golden in her heritage somewhere.

Likes:  Attention, being petted, belly rubs, food, having visitors, being spoken to kindly

Favorite Snack:  Not too picky, mostly eats Nudges and True Chews chicken treats, Full Moon Organic Chicken Treats, Blue Buffalo Wilderness Salmon Treats.  She also really enjoys salmon when once in a while added to her dinner.  Seems to love plain Organic Yogurt.  Also really likes the natural peanut butter I buy.  Also likes chew/dental bones (like Natural Balance Limited Ingredient Dental chews).  Sometimes will have a lickimat filled with peanut butter and canned food, sometimes does a snuffle mat with treats, or a quiet treat-dispensing toy

Eating Schedule:  2 meals a day, morning and evening, and also has snacks at different times.  

Signal for Potty: Does not signal for potty, she goes on schedule, however if she really really had to go, she would likely head to the door and start barking trying to get someone's attention, though that's only been on a very rare occasion. 

Personality:  She is just so pleasant.  A very happy girl.  Gets excited to be loved on or to have attention, happy to greet visitors.  Very sweet girl.  Not a barker unless she gets super excited (like when her favorite people visit).

Temperament:  Josie is pretty low-key, easy going, listens very well.  Pretty unasumming.  Very sweet.  

Energy Level:  Lower energy level, although that can be in part to surgery and recovery given the long period of confined rest she needed, and length of time to rebuild muscle and endurance.  She enjoys walks.  She does have prey-drive so will want to chase critters.  Off-leash in the backyard if she sees a critter, especially a rabbit, she will give chase.

Favorite Activities:  Getting loved on, relaxing on the couch, walks, loves car rides

Good with Cats, Dogs, and Kids over 6?:  Josie is fostered with 4 small dogs, though she doesn't really interact with any of them (she is afraid of the one that is not so nice to her sometimes).  Unknown how she would be with larger dogs though I would guess that overly excited/playful pups might be too much for her.  She has not been around cats.  She would likely be great with kids over 6. 

Not Good With:  Hmmmm, unsure how to answer that.  Has been good pretty much all the way around as far as what she's encountered in foster care. 

Housetrained: Yes

Crate Trained:  Josie is not crated at all, she has free run of the house, does not get into anything she shouldn't.  She was crated when she first came and then for a lengthy time for recovery after surgery as her activity needed greatly restricted and she did fine with it.  

Challenges:  Trying to teach her to 'sit' has been a real challenge, hehe.  

Any Medical Issues?:  Josie is still rebuilding strength and endurance after having a total hip replacement (and surgical repair of fracture at top of femur).  She does have some arthritis (degenerative changes) in the knee of the other leg, likely from some injury/trauma sustained long ago but nothing requiring surgical intervention

What would be the best kind of home?:  Josie's ideal home will be one where she will be spoiled, receiving lots of love and good care.  The more attention, the better for her, though she's not obnoxious or demanding in her wanting that attention.  She is happy just to take what she can get.  She loves her couch time and belly rubs, would be perfectly content to just settle in beside someone

Our adoption process starts with our application. Once the application is approved, a member of Legacy will contact you to set up a home visit. The home visit usually last 1-1 1/2 hours and is to make sure our dog and any current dogs/cats are getting along, as well as both of us agreeing it's a fit. At this time the adoption fee is due, and begins the 2 week trial. We will check in during the 2 week trial. If it's not working, our dog is returned to the foster home and all except $100.00 {$75 if Senior} of the adoption fee is returned. At the end of the 2 week trial, you decide if you will finalize the adoption - if finalized, the Adoption Contract is signed and all medical records are turned over to you. If at any time you need to rehome the dog it contractually needs to be returned to Legacy Dog Rescue.

ADOPTION FEE's:
Puppies under 6 months:  $199.00
Adults:  $150.00
Seniors (over 7 yrs):  $99.00

If you are interested in one of our dogs please fill out an application: 
https://form.jotform.com/193425528783165

animal.description:
Mickey (the boy) is 12 years old and weighs 12 pounds. Minnie (the girl) is 12 years old and weighs 6 pounds.

Hello out there,
We are Mickey and Minnie – the adorable doxypoos! OK, We may be named after those famous mice, but at least we don't have those ridiculously large, round ears and we are definitely larger – weighing in at a whopping 12 and 6 pounds respectively. Please, please don't ask us to sing the Mickey Mouse theme song though, because we do not know it. And our hair is definitely curlier than that giant mouse, but you wouldn't know it to see our latest haircut. If you adore curly, then just let it grow.

We've grown up together and always watch each other's backs. Minnie makes sure I get around ok and I do the same for her. I make sure she stays out of harm's way. We are very sad right now because the human we grew up with has recently passed away. We are overcome with grief, but would be even sadder if we were separated, so we fervently hope we are taken together – we love each other so much.

We are very friendly with children, though slightly nervous at first because we are so small and can be easily stepped on. After a bit though it is full speed ahead!

We can get a bit scared around strangers, but everyone turns into a friend soon. Play is our middle name and Snuggling is our second! If you give us a chance, you will soon have two best friends at the same time. What more could you want? Did we tell you that we like to snuggle? Yup, we love to snuggle.
 
Interested in MICKEY AND MINNIE? The first step is to fill out our online Adoption Application (address link below)

Note: All of our dogs live in foster homes so it is not possible to setup a meet and greet prior to submitting an adoption application. Filling out an application doesn't obligate you to adopt, but it does save your place in line if there are multiple people interested.
 
ADOPTION APPLICATION (Type or cut & paste the below website address into your browser): http://www.sdroregon.com/adoption-application.htm
 
If our Adoption Coordinator determines you are a good match they will contact you. This is a great opportunity for you to find out more about MICKEY AND MINNIE and decide if you would like to setup a meet and greet.  
 
ADOPTION FEE is $220 for the bonded pair.

 ADOPTION FEE is $150, and there’s a 10% Discount for Senior Citizens and Veterans.
 
We apologize, but we are not able to answer individual questions about our dogs. We are a small, all-volunteer organization and we receive hundreds of inquiries. If you want to learn more about a particular dog, then please submit an Adoption Application. If your application is chosen, you will have the opportunity to meet the dog and to get answers to all of your questions. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
A Lab-Chi??  Well, of course we do not know, we have not had a DNA. We couldn't figure out what this little girl might be. She acts like a lab, all full of love and fun, sniffs and smarts. But then on the other hand she can have a little bit of an attitude towards other much larger dogs, is only 30 pounds and has a lovely petite frame. How perfect is that for the person that would love a lab in their life but would prefer a more portable dog-lol!  

Emmie is just 2 years old. She originally came from Alabama and was adopted from a Chicago shelter when she was a wee one, just 7 pounds. Well here we are a couple years later, who knows what changed but this little girl got the short end of the stick. So many families are facing hardships due to the Covid, so not judgment there, but so sad for the dogs, cats and such that do not understand why they lost their family. She is doing very well tho since arriving in her foster home. She is a healthy, active girl, but was just a little too stressed at the shelter. She is thin and needs to gain some weight, but otherwise there are no health concerns. 

Emmie will do well in an active home, no small children, please. She will do well with anther active, social dog, one perhaps she can learn from and gain some confidence. Emmie is very loving with her people, she is just a little unsure of some dogs, especially much larger dogs. She is a little love of a dog that needs her happily ever after with a loving family/person. So many rescue dogs need extra TLC, so please, a home that has to be gone for long hours is not the right home for Emmie. She is an awesome, loving little girl, loves her toys, her pals, and big hugs. She will do best in a dog savvy home that will know how to make her feel safe and comfy in her new home. 

Emmie is fully vetted and microchipped.  Her adoption fee is $350, which is tax deductible. She comes with a free month of insurance if you would like and plenty of supplies to help her settle into her new home. Please email Kristine at joysparrows@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Meet Herc!  This valiant sweet sweet boy came to us in way of Tijuana Mexico. Swooped up from the streets, skin and bones with no muscle tone at all, having been pegged by a car, a Good Samaritan picked him up and whisked him to a vet right away. After committing to his rescue, he was given a clean bill of health (minus the malnourishment, no muscle tone and a sore hip) he came up to us in CA. Herc is a GREAT dog, loving to all, and as in his name, this boy LOVES to play ball and retrieve it!! We are letting him enjoy this game (and lots of long walks/hikes) to build up his muscle tone, which is coming along so well. 

This boy will need some house training (although he picks up so fast) and his lead training has been going extremely well.  He is an easy trained dog who listens well and loves on all.  

Herc is approx 10 months old. He is neutered, vaccinated, wormed, and microchipped.  He would make a fabulous family dog to go out on family road trips, camping and more!

animal.description:
Is Jackson still available??  GO TO OUR WEBSITE for up to date information to find out.  Check the Gallery by putting your mouse on the photo.  IF it says Pending, we chose someone, but they haven't met up yet.  If it says Adopted, then the dog has been happily united with a forever family.  IF nothing is there other than their name, they are still available.

APPLY if interested so you can be considered.

*Our page is updated daily. Please go to www.wowdogrescue.org for any updates.

Here is a sweet boy...LOVES all people, but was found being beat up by another dog. A lady stopped and helped break up the fight, and Jackson ended up with a gash on his head. It has been Vet checked, and he is on his way to recovery.  (Because of this incident, he may be a little nervous around bigger dogs...otherwise he seems fine.

He also was checked for his eyes that were running a lot and were itchy to him.. the vet feels he has allergies.  He is most likely a Poodle / Bichon mix.  Right around 4 yrs of age, and weighing in at 15 lbs.  He goes potty out side at the fosters home and loves to get any attention she will give him.

He sits by the door when he needs to go outside and Jackson has free run of the fosters home with no accidents.  Jackson is a fast walker, and he has been walking 2 miles every morning and 2 miles most evenings, (weather permitting), with a short afternoon walk sometimes thrown in the mix.

Not sure about his reaction of cats, but we do not feel that he would bother one.
He does fine with car rides.

Jackson likes to cuddle and he sleeps in bed with the foster.  He likes bully sticks for snacking on.

Jackson is the type of dog that will require regular grooming.  IF this is something you are un-able to maintain, please do not apply.

He has his rabies shot, Bordetella and DHPP done.  He is scheduled to be neutered, and get his microchip done 1/27/21.  Once he is healed he can be adopted.

Jackson's adoption fee is set at $275.00

WE ARE NOT PETFINDER.  WE ARE NOT ADOPTAPET OR RESCUE ME.  Our application is on our website:  www.wowdogrescue.org 

**PLEASE do not call to see if he is "still" available.  His Gallery photo on our website will be updated daily and will state his status.  IF we have chosen someone, he will be marked "Pending".  IF he has been adopted, he will be marked "Adopted".

***Tired of not finding, or not being chosen for the dog of your dream?? 
 Consider Fostering with us...Our Fosters have 1st chance at adopting the dog they foster, while we pay for everything.  Its a win win for both! YOU get to see if this is a good match for your family, while the dog is being loved in your home...

animal.description:
Omega is an adorable/wrinkly 10 week old American Bulldog/Boxer mix! 

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

****PETronus Rescue endeavors to include all pertinent information for each of the dogs within our organization with regard to approximate age, potty training status, kennel training status, temperament, activity level, dog/cat friendliness, etc in an effort to give those considering adopting as much information as we have.  Inquiries requesting additional information will not be returned, due to limited volunteers. Thank you for your understanding **** 

Meet Annabelle.

Annabelle is being returned to our rescue, along with her brother Chucky, due to their family being relocated to Australia for work.

She is estimated to have been born in June 2019, making her just over 1.5 years old. She is house broken, walks well on a leash, has moved past the chewing stage for the most part, is up to date on her vaccinations, spayed, microchipped, and LOVES to snuggle. 

She does great with people and other dogs but has not been cat tested.

—————————————

All PETronus Rescue dogs receive basic vaccinations (distemper/parvo, bordetella, & rabies), spay/ neuter, and microchip prior to adoption. We also treat any know medical issues, including heartworms.

Our dogs live in foster homes while they wait patiently for their forever families to find them. This is beneficial in that they learn house manners, crate training, housebreaking, etc while they wait and we are also able to get a very realistic picture of their energy level, temperament, etc so that we can place them in a home that is the best fit.

Our adoption fees are $200 for dogs over 1 year of age and $250 for dogs under 1 year of age. Puppies receive 3 rounds of puppy vaccinations.

If you are interested in adopting one of our amazing dogs, please fill out our adoption application here http://bit.ly/PRAdoption and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
Meet Viola!

Viola was found chained to a building down in Mexicali and Yuya Duran, and her local rescuer reached out for help. On January 24th, Viola made it across the border and up to FFF. Soon after Viola arrived, she went to live in a foster home to get extra TLC, and she's certainly getting it! They bathed her, learned her favorite meals to encourage her to eat, and equipped her with booties so she wouldn't slip on their floors.

We took Viola to College Animal Hospital for diagnostics. They reported that Viola is underweight and could probably put on another 10 pounds or so. Her x-rays showed some spondylosis (a type of arthritis caused by wear and tear to the spine) too, which may be why she walks timidly. She is missing many teeth and has some chronically worn teeth. Viola will have a dental on the same day as her spay. There were a few elevated values on her bloowork, so we're going to do an abdominal scan, too.

We received a great first update from Viola's foster mom: "Viola is just the sweetest gal there is! This little toothless beauty tolerates baths and grooming without a peep and gets along with other dogs and cats. No accidents in the home anymore, but I need to be super vigilant in taking her outside. Viola doesn't know how to ask. She's getting feisty and stronger by the day. A big fan of Wendy's frosties and assisted strolls on the beach/dog park!"

Be sure to watch the cute video of Viola playing with a toy!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
Max 
Pittsburgh, PA

Meet Max!  This little guy is THE sweetest ever! Max is a senior Min Pin (10-12 years old) who found himself in a bad situation. Thankfully someone stood up and removed Max from that situation and helped him make his way to DDR. At one point in Max's life, someone actually kicked Max into a wall. Thankfully Max survived, but unfortunately he did suffer some neurological damage from the incident. He can walk and get around, but he is wobbly and most certainly can never have access to stairs. He would most certainly fall down the stairs and hurt himself further. He also has a bit of a head tilt due to the neurological trauma.
This charismatic little guy is definitely special needs, but such a total love! He is super affectionate and wants nothing more than to be with his foster mom. He LOVES giving kisses, being held, and curling up on her lap. While he loves being his velcro self, Max also loves everyone he meets. He is great in the car and he also gets along with every dog he meets. Max would do fine in a home with other CALM dogs or as an only dog. Again, NO STAIRS for MAX and he cannot go on walks. A quiet home looking for a sweet companion to spend time with would be his ideal forever home. Dog savvy children over the age of 16 only. 

If you are interested in this little guy please visit our website www.ddrinc.net to fill out an application. 
Pittsburgh, PA

animal.description:
If you are looking for an adult dog with demeanor of a lady, Hannah is the dog for you!  This girl loves going on walks, playing with toys, watching wildlife from the window and cuddling with her human.  What she loves the most are belly rubs, hugs and kisses.  You can see her huge smile and her eyes would squint when she’s happy. She has the kindest eyes and a heartwarming face that will light up your day.  She loves sleeping in bed and being tucked in right next to you for extra warmth.  She also enjoys her "pawdicure" -- she will sit and hand you her paw as if it's bonding time.  The vet loves her and always comments on what a sweet girl she is!  

 As sweet as Hannah is, she is extremely shy, especially with new people.  She’s looking for someone who will be patient and give her time to know you and adjust to her new surroundings.  She would love a quiet home with another dog sibling to show her the ropes.  Also, a fenced-in backyard would be a plus but not absolutely necessary, so long as she gets her daily walks.  Hannah is 8 years old, weighs 55 lbs., is spayed and vaccinated.  To adopt this black beauty, please contact Pyul at pyul.strayfromtheheart@gmail.com or fill out our on-line adoption application at strayfromtheheart.org.

animal.description:
MEET OZZIE – 4 year Rottie Mix. Little Ozzie was brought into a large Tennessee animal control on December 22nd. There he sat through Christmas waiting for his family to find him, someone to adopt or a rescue to help.  He sat there through New Years and into January when he was brought to our attention. Ozzie is affectionately described as a sweet boy with the cutest little wiggle and happy dance. He can sit, shake and speak. And does this boy like to talk…If he has something to say about anything he will tell you. He would be in heaven if he has a sofa where he can lay and stretch his legs.
Ozzie is only 45 lbs., he has the look and colors of a rottie, but his is mixed with another breed that will keep him on the small.  He does well with other dogs, but we do not know about cats. He is housebroken but might need time to readjust to a new home.  If there are children in his new home, they should be over the age of 7.
If you are interested in including OZZIE in your home, please go to our website Placement Page http://www.recycledrotts.org/wp/?page_id=150 for the rescue location, placement policies, placement fee and the link to our online application.

animal.description:
Meet Whit! He came to us with an amputated hind leg, a broken pelvis and was heartworm positive. It has taken us some time, but he is healthy and ready to start his new life! Whit is a 2-year-old Walker Hound who weighs 57lbs. He loves everyone and everything; dogs, cats, kids, and life itself! We have only heard Whit bark a handful of times over the last few months. He will need a fenced yard; he knows how to use a dog door and likes to come and go as he pleases. Whit travels well; he has been out running errands and loves hanging out at breweries. If you are looking for a loving dog to spoil, look no further!

If you are interested in adoption; DO NOT CALL, please complete an online application on 4 Paws Animal Rescue's website at www.4pawz.org. We verify the care of past/current pets as well as home information. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs and cats, and therefore, we reserve the right to approve or deny an application based on what we determine is in the pet's best interest.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description: Kiwi is a rambunctious little 1 year old pup who loves to wrestle and play tug-of-war! He’s a sweet little velcro dog with tons of puppy energy. He loves people, children, and other dogs, but does get nervous in new surroundings and can get overwhelmed on walks and at the dog park so he’ll need a patient family to teach him that he’s safe and free to explore. He’s the perfect candidate for obedience training as he’s a clean slate, and is currently learning to sit and wait for his food. He is still house and crate training with frequent potty breaks, and will benefit greatly with a nice backyard to run around in, perhaps with an older dog companion to show him the ropes. For more information please contact Chris at Chris@staranimalrescue.org
